irne, Calgary's Jack Long, and Edmonton's Peter Hemingway. Apart from the documentation of the twelve houses (drawings and photos), there are interpretative essays on each. A co-authored introductory essay explores several related themes: modernity, the contemporary house, approaches to landscape, and the role of drawings in contemporary practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture, DomesticzCanadavExhibitions. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th centuryvExhibitions. 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / Residential.2bisacsh1 aMcMordie, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSimmins, Geoffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552384664?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552384664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552384664/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles